Call by value passes a copy of the variable's value, so changes inside the function do not affect the original. Call by reference passes the address (using pointers), so changes affect the original.

```c
// Call by value
void changeVal(int x) { x = 10; }

// Call by reference
void changeRef(int *x) { *x = 10; }
```

malloc() allocates a single block of uninitialized memory. calloc() allocates multiple blocks and initializes all bytes to zero.
Syntax:
malloc(size_in_bytes);
calloc(num_elements, element_size);

